  <!-- CSS Properties Section -->
  <section>
    <h2 id="css-properties">CSS Properties</h2>

    <code-block language="css" label="Horizontal rule CSS styles">{{ cssPropertiesCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <h3>Key Features</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>No default border</strong> - Resets browser default to use custom styling</li>
      <li><strong>Logical properties</strong> - Uses <code>border-block-start</code> for RTL support</li>
      <li><strong>Generous spacing</strong> - <code>margin-block: var(--size-xl)</code> for clear separation</li>
      <li><strong>Decorative content</strong> - Uses <code>::before</code> pseudo-element for dots</li>
      <li><strong>Custom ornament</strong> - Uses <code>attr(data-ornament)</code> for user-defined symbols</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Customization</h3>
    <p>You can customize the horizontal rule with CSS custom properties:</p>
    <code-block language="css" label="Customization examples">{{ customizationCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <!-- Accessibility Section -->
  <section>
    <h2 id="accessibility">Accessibility</h2>

    <h3>Semantic Meaning</h3>
    <p>The <code>&lt;hr&gt;</code> element has an implicit ARIA role of <code>separator</code>. Screen readers may announce it as a separator or horizontal rule, helping users understand the content structure.</p>

    <h3>Best Practices</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Use for thematic breaks only</strong> - Don't use hr for purely visual decoration</li>
      <li><strong>Consider context</strong> - Ensure the break makes sense without visual styling</li>
      <li><strong>Don't overuse</strong> - Too many breaks can be disorienting for screen reader users</li>
      <li><strong>Combine with headings</strong> - For major sections, a heading may be more appropriate</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>ARIA Considerations</h3>
    <p>If using hr purely for decoration, you can hide it from screen readers:</p>
    <code-block language="html" label="Hidden from screen readers">{{ ariaHiddenCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>However, this is generally not recommended. If the break is meaningful, it should be announced. If it's purely decorative, consider using CSS borders instead.</p>
  </section>

